{"ts":"2026-06-27T22:47:00.696Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_end","contentType":"tool","toolName":"read_files","toolCallId":"34ca9yqw","output":[{"query":"/Users/ayushbansal/Documents/GitHub/hirezapp_landing_page/docs/PHASE_6_AWS_FINAL_SETUP.md","result":"  1 | # GFF AI Platform: Phase 6 AWS Production Deployment & Data Modeling Guide\n  2 | \n  3 | This document defines the enterprise AWS cloud migration strategy for the **GFF AI Platform** from the local Phase 5 sandbox. It specifies the exact schemas for three required DynamoDB tables, an S3 storage bucket, and the required environment parameters.\n  4 | \n  5 | ---\n  6 | \n  7 | ## 1. Cloud-Native Serverless Architecture\n  8 | \n  9 | ```\n 10 | +------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------+\n 11 | |                               PHASE 6 ENTERPRISE AWS TOPOLOGY                                  |\n 12 | |  [ SECURE CLIENTS ] ==( HTTPS / TLS 1.3 )==> [ API GATEWAY ] ==> [ FASTAPI ON AWS LAMBDA ]    |\n 13 | |                                                                          |                     |\n 14 | |  [ S3 STORAGE BUCKET ] <--(Presigned URLs)-------------------------------+                     |\n 15 | |  (gff-portal-documents)                                                  v                     |\n 16 | |                                                                 [ AMAZON DYNAMODB ]            |\n 17 | |                                                                 - GFF_USERS                    |\n 18 | |                                                                 - GFF_CLIENTS                  |\n 19 | |                                                                 - GFF_PORTAL_ITEMS             |\n 20 | +------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------+\n 21 | ```\n 22 | \n 23 | ---\n 24 | \n 25 | ## 2. Production DynamoDB Data Modeling\n 26 | \n 27 | Exactly **three** DynamoDB tables are used. Complex workspace and transactional entities are modeled inside a single-table architecture (`GFF_PORTAL_ITEMS`) using custom Partition Keys (`PK`) and Sort Keys (`SK`).\n 28 | \n 29 | ### 2.1. Table Map Overview\n 30 | | Table Name | Partition Key (PK) | Sort Key (SK) | Global Secondary Index (GSI) | Purpose |\n 31 | | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |\n 32 | | **`GFF_USERS`** | `email` (String) | *None* | *None* | Global user registry and access credentials. |\n 33 | | **`GFF_CLIENTS`** | `client_id` (String) | *None* | *None* | Enterprise customer accounts. |\n 34 | | **`GFF_PORTAL_ITEMS`** | `PK` (String) | `SK` (String) | `GSI1` (using `GSI1PK` & `GSI1SK`) | Multi-tenant workspace record store. |\n 35 | \n 36 | ### 2.2. Table Definition: `GFF_USERS`\n 37 | *   **Table Name**: `GFF_USERS`\n 38 | *   **Primary Key**: `email` (String)\n 39 | *   **Example Item**: `{\"email\": \"admin@client.com\", \"role\": \"admin\", \"client_id\": \"client_gff_01\"}`\n 40 | \n 41 | ### 2.3. Table Definition: `GFF_CLIENTS`\n 42 | *   **Table Name**: `GFF_CLIENTS`\n 43 | *   **Primary Key**: `client_id` (String)\n 44 | *   **Example Item**: `{\"client_id\": \"client_gff_01\", \"company_name\": \"Sovereign Logistics Corp\", \"tier\": \"ENTERPRISE\"}`\n 45 | \n 46 | ### 2.4. Single-Table Definition: `GFF_PORTAL_ITEMS`\n 47 | *   **Table Name**: `GFF_PORTAL_ITEMS`\n 48 | *   **Primary Key**: `PK` (String), `SK` (String)\n 49 | *   **GSI Name**: `GSI1` (using `GSI1PK` and `GSI1SK`)\n 50 | *   **Purpose**: Single-table design housing the 6 core operational models of the GFF AI Portal.\n 51 | \n 52 | #### Entity Mappings & Storage Patterns\n 53 | \n 54 | 1. **Projects**\n 55 |    - **`PK`**: `CLIENT#<client_id>` | **`SK`**: `PROJ#<project_id>`\n 56 |    - **`GSI1PK`**: `PROJ#<project_id>` | **`GSI1SK`**: `METADATA`\n 57 |    - **Attributes**: `name`, `status`, `progress`, `budget`, `created_at`\n 58 | \n 59 | 2. **AI Operations**\n 60 |    - **`PK`**: `CLIENT#<client_id>` | **`SK`**: `AIOPS#<ops_id>`\n 61 |    - **`GSI1PK`**: `PROJ#<project_id>` (links to project) | **`GSI1SK`**: `AIOPS#<ops_id>`\n 62 |    - **Attributes**: `name`, `status`, `agent_count`, `runtime_seconds`, `cpu_usage`, `memory_usage`\n 63 | \n 64 | 3. **Documents Metadata**\n 65 |    - **`PK`**: `CLIENT#<client_id>` | **`SK`**: `DOC#<doc_id>`\n 66 |    - **`GSI1PK`**: `PROJ#<project_id>` (retrieves files by project) | **`GSI1SK`**: `DOC#<doc_id>`\n 67 |    - **Attributes**: `title`, `s3_key`, `file_size`, `category`, `uploaded_by`, `uploaded_at`\n 68 | \n 69 | 4. **Invoices Metadata**\n 70 |    - **`PK`**: `CLIENT#<client_id>` | **`SK`**: `INV#<invoice_id>`\n 71 |    - **`GSI1PK`**: `BILLING_PERIOD#<year_month>` | **`GSI1SK`**: `INV#<invoice_id>`\n 72 |    - **Attributes**: `amount_usd`, `status`, `due_date`, `epochs_consumed`, `created_at`\n 73 | \n 74 | 5. **Support Tickets**\n 75 |    - **`PK`**: `CLIENT#<client_id>` | **`SK`**: `TICKET#<ticket_id>`\n 76 |    - **`GSI1PK`**: `STATUS#<status_code>` (supports dashboard queues) | **`GSI1SK`**: `TICKET#<ticket_id>`\n 77 |    - **Attributes**: `subject`, `priority`, `status_text`, `assigned_to`, `created_at`\n 78 | \n 79 | 6. **Governance Items**\n 80 |    - **`PK`**: `CLIENT#<client_id>` | **`SK`**: `GOV#<gov_id>`\n 81 |    - **`GSI1PK`**: `STANDARD#<compliance_standard>` | **`GSI1SK`**: `GOV#<gov_id>`\n 82 |    - **Attributes**: `control_name`, `status`, `remediation_notes`, `assessed_at`\n 83 | \n 84 | ---\n 85 | \n 86 | ## 3. Cloud Object Storage Setup (Amazon S3)\n 87 | \n 88 | *   **Bucket Reference**: `gff-portal-documents-prod`\n 89 | *   **Security Configurations**:\n 90 |     *   **Block Public Access**: Enabled.\n 91 |     *   **Encryption at Rest**: Enforced using KMS customer-managed keys (SSE-KMS).\n 92 |     *   **Secure Transport**: Restricts transport to TLS 1.3/HTTPS.\n 93 |     *   **Presigned Access**: Frontend uploads/downloads via short-lived pre-signed URLs generated by Lambda (valid for 15 minutes).\n 94 | \n 95 | ---\n 96 | \n 97 | ## 4. Required Deployment Environment Keys\n 98 | \n 99 | ### 4.1. Next.js Frontend Keys (`.env.production`)\n100 | ```env\n101 | NEXT_PUBLIC_API_BASE_URL=https://api.gff.ai/v1\n102 | NEXT_PUBLIC_APP_ENV=production\n103 | NEXT_PUBLIC_PORTAL_UPLOADS_ENABLED=true\n104 | NEXT_PUBLIC_S3_BUCKET_NAME=gff-portal-documents-prod\n105 | ```\n106 | \n107 | ### 4.2. FastAPI AWS Backend Keys (`backend/prod.env` / Lambda Variables)\n108 | ```env\n109 | PROJECT_NAME=\"GFF AI Enterprise Cloud Engine\"\n110 | API_V1_STR=\"/api/v1\"\n111 | ENVIRONMENT=\"production\"\n112 | CORS_ORIGINS=\"https://portal.gff.ai,https://admin.gff.ai\"\n113 | FRONTEND_BASE_URL=\"https://portal.gff.ai\"\n114 | AWS_REGION=us-east-1\n115 | AWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID=production_aws_access_key_id\n116 | AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY=production_aws_secret_access_key\n117 | DYNAMODB_USERS_TABLE=GFF_USERS\n118 | DYNAMODB_CLIENTS_TABLE=GFF_CLIENTS\n119 | DYNAMODB_ITEMS_TABLE=GFF_PORTAL_ITEMS\n120 | DYNAMODB_ITEMS_TYPE_INDEX=GSI1\n121 | S3_DOCUMENTS_BUCKET=gff-portal-documents-prod\n122 | S3_DOCUMENTS_PREFIX=clients\n123 | JWT_SECRET=production_cryptographically_secure_256_bit_signature_key_2026\n124 | ACCESS_TOKEN_EXPIRE_MINUTES=1440\n125 | ```\n126 | \n127 | \n128 | ---\n129 | \n130 | ## 5. Seeded User Credentials (Final MVP Data)\n131 | \n132 | The system contains exactly **four** seeded user accounts covering the three standard RBAC roles (`gff_admin`, `client_admin`, `client_member`). All passwords, roles, and client associations are modeled to enable immediate high-fidelity secure testing.\n133 | \n134 | | Role | Email | Password | Associated Client | Notes |\n135 | | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |\n136 | | **`gff_admin`** | `gff_admin@gff.ai` | `password123` | *None* | Global platform administrator. Accesses the GFF Admin Panel. |\n137 | | **`client_admin`** | `client_admin@apex.com` | `password123` | `Apex Global Solutions` (ID: 1) | Enterprise client administrator. Full workspace management for Client 1. |\n138 | | **`client_member`** | `client_member@apex.com` | `password123` | `Apex Global Solutions` (ID: 1) | Client 1 standard user. Limited operational access inside Client 1 workspace. |\n139 | | **`client_member`** | `client@chevron.com` | `chevron_secure_pass_2026` | `Sovereign Logistics Corp` (ID: 2) | Client 2 standard user. Used to verify cross-tenant security and upload/download boundaries in smoke tests. |\n140 | \n141 | These credentials can be used both locally (via SQLite/mock fallbacks) and in the production cloud (AWS DynamoDB) once the environment is initialized and seeded using:\n142 | ```bash\n143 | npm run backend:seed\n144 | ```\n145 | \n146 | \n147 | \n148 | ---\n149 | \n150 | ## 6. Execution, Build, and Deployment Manual\n151 | \n152 | This section outlines the operational commands, deployment procedures, required environment parameters, and AWS production resources for launching the GFF AI Platform.\n153 | \n154 | ### 6.1. Backend Execution & Deployment Commands\n155 | \n156 | The backend is built as a cloud-ready FastAPI application that can be run locally using Uvicorn or deployed to AWS Lambda (e.g., using Mangum adapter) or AWS App Runner / Elastic Beanstalk.\n157 | \n158 | #### 1. Setup & Installation\n159 | To create the virtual environment and install all python dependencies, run:\n160 | ```bash\n161 | # From project root\n162 | npm run backend:install\n163 | \n164 | # Or from backend directory\n165 | cd backend\n166 | python3 -m venv venv\n167 | source venv/bin/activate\n168 | pip install -r requirements.txt\n169 | ```\n170 | \n171 | #### 2. Seed Database\n172 | To seed the database with multi-tenant workspace credentials, projects, operations, invoices, support tickets, and compliance logs:\n173 | ```bash\n174 | # From project root\n175 | npm run backend:seed\n176 | \n177 | # Or from backend directory with active virtual environment\n178 | cd backend\n179 | python app/seed.py\n180 | ```\n181 | \n182 | #### 3. Run Backend Start Command (Development/Production)\n183 | To launch the FastAPI ASGI server:\n184 | ```bash\n185 | # From project root (hot-reload enabled)\n186 | npm run backend:dev\n187 | \n188 | # From backend directory (standard FastAPI startup)\n189 | cd backend\n190 | venv/bin/uvicorn app.main:app --host 0.0.0.0 --port 8000\n191 | ```\n192 | *For production cloud environments (e.g., AWS App Runner or EC2), execute:*\n193 | ```bash\n194 | uvicorn app.main:app --host 0.0.0.0 --port 8000 --workers 4\n195 | ```\n196 | \n197 | #### 4. Backend Health & Smoke Checks\n198 | To execute complete RBAC, JWT, and multi-tenancy isolation tests:\n199 | ```bash\n200 | # From project root\n201 | npm run backend:check\n202 | \n203 | # Or from backend directory\n204 | cd backend\n205 | ./venv/bin/pytest app/test_backend_smoke.py\n206 | ./venv/bin/python app/test_security_utilities.py\n207 | ./venv/bin/python app/test_clients_api.py\n208 | ```\n209 | \n210 | ---\n211 | \n212 | ### 6.2. Next.js Frontend Execution & Build Commands\n213 | \n214 | The frontend is an enterprise-grade Next.js App Router workspace optimized for modern deployment platforms (Vercel, AWS Amplify, AWS ECS, or S3/CloudFront for static builds).\n215 | \n216 | #### 1. Frontend Build Command\n217 | To produce an optimized production-ready bundle:\n218 | ```bash\n219 | # From project root\n220 | npm run build\n221 | ```\n222 | This command compiles the TypeScript components, static assets, and App Router pages into the `.next` production distribution.\n223 | \n224 | #### 2. Frontend Start Command\n225 | To run the built production frontend server:\n226 | ```bash\n227 | # From project root\n228 | npm run start\n229 | ```\n230 | \n231 | #### 3. Frontend Development Command\n232 | To launch the local development hot-reloading server:\n233 | ```bash\n234 | # From project root\n235 | npm run dev\n236 | ```\n237 | \n238 | ---\n239 | \n240 | ### 6.3. Complete Production Environment Variables\n241 | \n242 | #### Backend Environment Variables\n243 | These variables must be configured in AWS Parameter Store, AWS Secrets Manager, or as environment variables on the hosting container/Lambda:\n244 | \n245 | | Variable Name | Required Value/Format | Purpose |\n246 | | :--- | :--- | :--- |\n247 | | `PROJECT_NAME` | `\"GFF AI Enterprise Cloud Engine\"` | API title metadata |\n248 | | `API_V1_STR` | `\"/api/v1\"` | API prefix path |\n249 | | `ENVIRONMENT` | `\"production\"` | Set runtime stage |\n250 | | `CORS_ORIGINS` | `https://portal.gff.ai,https://admin.gff.ai` | Allowed frontend domains (CORS compliance) |\n251 | | `FRONTEND_BASE_URL` | `https://portal.gff.ai` | Root URL of client-facing portal |\n252 | | `AWS_REGION` | `us-east-1` (or chosen region) | Target region for DynamoDB and S3 |\n253 | | `AWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID` | *production_aws_access_key_id* | AWS IAM deployer credentials |\n254 | | `AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY` | *production_aws_secret_access_key* | AWS IAM deployer secret |\n255 | | `DYNAMODB_USERS_TABLE` | `GFF_USERS` | DynamoDB user registry table |\n256 | | `DYNAMODB_CLIENTS_TABLE` | `GFF_CLIENTS` | DynamoDB enterprise client registry table |\n257 | | `DYNAMODB_ITEMS_TABLE` | `GFF_PORTAL_ITEMS` | Multi-tenant operational records store |\n258 | | `DYNAMODB_ITEMS_TYPE_INDEX` | `GSI1` | Global Secondary Index for single-table queries |\n259 | | `S3_DOCUMENTS_BUCKET` | `gff-portal-documents-prod` | Secure client document storage |\n260 | | `S3_DOCUMENTS_PREFIX` | `clients` | File key namespace prefix |\n261 | | `JWT_SECRET` | *cryptographically_secure_256_bit_signature_key* | Cryptographic token signing secret |\n262 | | `ACCESS_TOKEN_EXPIRE_MINUTES` | `1440` (24 hours) | Token lifespan limit |\n263 | \n264 | #### Frontend Environment Variables\n265 | These variables must be set in the build pipeline (e.g. Vercel dashboard, AWS Amplify console):\n266 | \n267 | | Variable Name | Required Value/Format | Purpose |\n268 | | :--- | :--- | :--- |\n269 | | `NEXT_PUBLIC_API_BASE_URL` | `https://api.gff.ai/v1` | URL pointing to the FastAPI gateway |\n270 | | `NEXT_PUBLIC_APP_ENV` | `production` | Deployment stage tag |\n271 | | `NEXT_PUBLIC_PORTAL_UPLOADS_ENABLED` | `true` | Enables upload features on Client Portal |\n272 | | `NEXT_PUBLIC_S3_BUCKET_NAME` | `gff-portal-documents-prod` | Target S3 bucket name |\n273 | \n274 | ---\n275 | \n276 | ### 6.4. AWS Production Cloud Resource Names\n277 | \n278 | Ensure the following exact resource names are created in your target AWS account to match the production configuration defaults:\n279 | \n280 | 1. **Amazon DynamoDB Tables**:\n281 |    - `GFF_USERS` (Primary Key: `email` [String])\n282 |    - `GFF_CLIENTS` (Primary Key: `client_id` [String])\n283 |    - `GFF_PORTAL_ITEMS` (Primary Key: `PK` [String], Sort Key: `SK` [String], GSI: `GSI1` with PK `GSI1PK` [String] and SK `GSI1SK` [String])\n284 | \n285 | 2. **Amazon S3 Storage Bucket**:\n286 |    - `gff-portal-documents-prod` (Block All Public Access, KMS SSE-KMS Encryption, TLS 1.3 Secure Transport enforced)\n287 | \n288 | 3. **AWS IAM Execution Role Policy**:\n289 |    - Create a role with a minimum privilege boundary allowing full read/write access to the three DynamoDB tables above, and pre-signed URL generation access on the `gff-portal-documents-prod` S3 bucket.\n290 | ","success":true},{"query":"/Users/ayushbansal/Documents/GitHub/hirezapp_landing_page/next.config.ts","result":" 1 | import type { NextConfig } from \"next\";\n 2 | \n 3 | const nextConfig: NextConfig = {\n 4 |   async redirects() {\n 5 |     return [\n 6 |       {\n 7 |         source: \"/landing_page\",\n 8 |         destination: \"/\",\n 9 |         permanent: true,\n10 |       },\n11 |       {\n12 |         source: \"/landing_page/:path*\",\n13 |         destination: \"/:path*\",\n14 |         permanent: true,\n15 |       },\n16 |       {\n17 |         source: \"/experience\",\n18 |         destination: \"/#experience\",\n19 |         permanent: true,\n20 |       },\n21 |     ];\n22 |   },\n23 | };\n24 | \n25 | export default nextConfig;","success":true}],"durationMs":7}}
