llow you to manage and run the backend seamlessly without manually creating or activating Python virtual environments in your active terminal.\\n 10 | \\n 11 | From the **root directory** of the project, you can run:\\n 12 | \\n 13 | *   **Install Backend Dependencies & Environment Setup**:\\n 14 |     ```bash\\n 15 |     npm run backend:install\\n 16 |     ```\\n 17 |     *This automatically creates the Python virtual environment (`venv`), installs all required pip dependencies, and copies `.env.example` to `.env` if not already present.*\\n 18 | \\n 19 | *   **Initialize & Seed Local SQLite Database**:\\n 20 |     ```bash\\n 21 |     npm run backend:seed\\n 22 |     ```\\n 23 |     *This executes the database seeder to bootstrap SQLite (`dev.db`) with multi-tenant enterprise development data (including GFF Admin, Apex Tenant Admin, Apex Client Members, as well as mock client accounts, projects, support tickets, invoices, and compliance logs).*\\n 24 | \\n 25 | *   **Run Backend Development Server (FastAPI)**:\\n 26 |     ```bash\\n 27 |     npm run backend:dev\\n 28 |     ```\\n 29 |     *Starts the FastAPI application via Uvicorn on [http://localhost:8000](http://localhost:8000) with hot-reloading enabled.*\\n 30 | \\n 31 | *   **Run Backend Security & Dependency Tests**:\\n 32 |     ```bash\\n 33 |     npm run backend:check\\n 34 |     ```\\n 35 |     *Executes the backend verification suite (`test_security_utilities.py`) to validate JWT token parsing, password bcrypt hashing, and role-based access control (RBAC) rules.*\\n 36 | \\n 37 | ---\\n 38 | \\n 39 | ## Architecture Overview\\n 40 | \\n 41 | The backend uses a standard, modular clean-architecture layout built for Python 3.12+ and FastAPI:\\n 42 | \\n 43 | ```text\\n 44 | backend/\\n 45 | ├── app/\\n 46 | │   ├── __init__.py\\n 47 | │   ├── api.py           # Core endpoints (Health, SystemLogs)\\n 48 | │   ├── config.py        # Settings & Pydantic Config Validation\\n 49 | │   ├── database.py      # SQLAlchemy DB Connection & Dependency Injection\\n 50 | │   ├── main.py          # FastAPI App Entrypoint & CORS Middleware\\n 51 | │   ├── models.py        # SQLAlchemy Declarative Models\\n 52 | │   └── schemas.py       # Pydantic Schemas (V2)\\n 53 | ├── .env.example         # Template for environment configuration\\n 54 | ├── .gitignore           # Local development ignores\\n 55 | ├── README.md            # Execution manual\\n 56 | └── requirements.txt     # Python Dependencies\\n 57 | ```\\n 58 | \\n 59 | ## Features\\n 60 | \\n 61 | - **Automated DB Bootstrap**: Automatically boots a local SQLite database (`dev.db`) on application launch.\\n 62 | - **Enterprise Logs**: A simple, high-performance database logger schema for auditing backend/frontend handshakes.\\n 63 | - **Health Verification**: An endpoint at `/api/v1/health` that dynamically validates database status and platform health.\\n 64 | - **Next.js Alignment**: Built-in CORS and request timing telemetry middleware matching frontend-dev requirements.\\n 65 | - **Clean Interactive Specs**: Automatic redirect of root `/` path to the interactive OpenAPI UI (`/docs`).\\n 66 | \\n 67 | ---\\n 68 | \\n 69 | ## Local Setup & Run Guide\\n 70 | \\n 71 | ### 1. Prerequisites\\n 72 | Ensure you have **Python 3.12+** and **pip** installed:\\n 73 | ```bash\\n 74 | python3 --version\\n 75 | pip3 --version\\n 76 | ```\\n 77 | \\n 78 | ### 2. Set Up Virtual Environment\\n 79 | Move to the backend folder and create a clean Python virtual environment:\\n 80 | ```bash\\n 81 | cd backend\\n 82 | python3 -m venv venv\\n 83 | ```\\n 84 | \\n 85 | Activate the environment:\\n 86 | - **macOS / Linux**:\\n 87 |   ```bash\\n 88 |   source venv/bin/activate\\n 89 |   ```\\n 90 | - **Windows**:\\n 91 |   ```bash\\n 92 |   venv\\\\Scripts\\\\activate\\n 93 |   ```\\n 94 | \\n 95 | ### 3. Install Dependencies\\n 96 | ```bash\\n 97 | pip install -r requirements.txt\\n 98 | ```\\n 99 | \\n100 | ### 4. Set Up Environment Config\\n101 | Copy the example environment file:\\n102 | ```bash\\n103 | cp .env.example .env\\n104 | ```\\n105 | The defaults in `.env` are pre-tuned for seamless local development with the Next.js local frontend.\\n106 | \\n107 | > ⚠️ **Production Security Warning**:\\n108 | > In local development mode, `JWT_SECRET` defaults to a safe developer-only fallback key. However, for any production deployment, you **MUST** override `JWT_SECRET` in your environment variables with a cryptographically secure, high-entropy key (e.g., generated via `openssl rand -hex 32`). Leaving the default key active in production compromises token verification and authentication security.\\n109 | \\n110 | ### 5. Seed the Local Database\\n111 | Seed the SQLite database with representative GFF AI multi-tenant development data (including 4 client accounts, 4 projects, 4 agent operations, 4 documents, 4 invoices, 3 support tickets, and 3 governance compliance records) and pre-configured role-based development users:\\n112 | \\n113 | ```bash\\n114 | python app/seed.py\\n115 | ```\\n116 | \\n117 | #### Pre-Configured Developer Accounts & Roles:\\n118 | - **GFF Admin Lead** (Global Operations):\\n119 |   - Email: `gff_admin@gff.ai`\\n120 |   - Role: `gff_admin`\\n121 |   - Password: `password123`\\n122 | - **Apex Admin Lead** (Client Tenant Admin):\\n123 |   - Email: `client_admin@apex.com`\\n124 |   - Role: `client_admin`\\n125 |   - Tenant: Apex Global\\n126 |   - Password: `password123`\\n127 | - **Apex Analyst** (Client Tenant Member):\\n128 |   - Email: `client_member@apex.com`\\n129 |   - Role: `client_member`\\n130 |   - Tenant: Apex Global\\n131 |   - Password: `password123`\\n132 | - **Legacy Fallback Admin**:\\n133 |   - Email: `admin@gff.ai`\\n134 |   - Role: `admin`\\n135 |   - Password: `gff_enterprise_admin_pass_2026`\\n136 | - **Legacy Fallback Client**:\\n137 |   - Email: `client@chevron.com`\\n138 |   - Role: `client`\\n139 |   - Tenant: Chevron Corporation\\n140 |   - Password: `chevron_secure_pass_2026`\\n141 | \\n142 | #### Idempotency & Database Resetting:\\n143 | - Running `python app/seed.py` repeatedly is perfectly **idempotent**; it checks for existing records before inserting, ensuring no duplicated keys or rows.\\n144 | - To safely **wipe all tables and fresh-seed** a clean slate, run with the `--reset` flag:\\n145 |   ```bash\\n146 |   python app/seed.py --reset\\n147 |   ```\\n148 | \\n149 | ### 6. Run the Server\\n150 | Launch the development server via Uvicorn:\\n151 | ```bash\\n152 | uvicorn app.main:app --reload --port 8000\\n153 | ```\\n154 | \\n155 | Once running, you can access:\\n156 | - **Interactive OpenAPI Documentation**: [http://localhost:8000/docs](http://localhost:8000/docs)\\n157 | - **Service Health Check Endpoint**: [http://localhost:8000/api/v1/health](http://localhost:8000/api/v1/health)\\n158 | \\n159 | ---\\n160 | \\n161 | ## API Documentation\\n162 | \\n163 | ### GET `/api/v1/health`\\n164 | Checks backend and database health.\\n165 | **Response (200 OK)**:\\n166 | ```json\\n167 | {\\n168 |   \\\"status\\\": \\\"healthy\\\",\\n169 |   \\\"timestamp\\\": 1719493200.0,\\n170 |   \\\"database\\\": {\\n171 |     \\\"status\\\": \\\"healthy\\\",\\n172 |     \\\"error\\\": null\\n173 |   },\\n174 |   \\\"services\\\": {\\n175 |     \\\"api\\\": \\\"healthy\\\",\\n176 |     \\\"gff_core\\\": \\\"operational\\\"\\n177 |   },\\n178 |   \\\"version\\\": \\\"1.0.0\\\"\\n179 | }\\n180 | ```\\n181 | \\n182 | ### GET `/api/v1/logs`\\n183 | Returns the recent list of system log entries.\\n184 | **Response (200 OK)**:\\n185 | ```json\\n186 | []\\n187 | ```\\n188 | \\n189 | ### POST `/api/v1/logs`\\n190 | Creates a test system log.\\n191 | **Request Payload**:\\n192 | ```json\\n193 | {\\n194 |   \\\"level\\\": \\\"INFO\\\",\\n195 |   \\\"message\\\": \\\"Next.js frontend handshake completed successfully\\\",\\n196 |   \\\"module\\\": \\\"handshake\\\"\\n197 | }\\n198 | ```\\n199 | **Response (201 Created)**:\\n200 | ```json\\n201 | {\\n202 |   \\\"id\\\": 1,\\n203 |   \\\"level\\\": \\\"INFO\\\",\\n204 |   \\\"message\\\": \\\"Next.js frontend handshake completed successfully\\\",\\n205 |   \\\"module\\\": \\\"handshake\\\",\\n206 |   \\\"created_at\\\": \\\"2026-06-27T15:10:00.000000\\\"\\n207 | }\\n208 | ```\",\"success\":true}],\"durationMs\":6}}\n./automation/tasks.json:    \"prompt\": \"This is the first task of Phase 5. Do not edit files. Audit the current project after Phase 4. Inspect the frontend stack, package.json, app routes, portal routes, admin routes, login pages, local auth preview utilities, local mock data, portal/admin components, docs from Phase 4, and any existing backend/API folders. Determine the safest MVP backend approach for this project. Default target architecture should be a separate local backend folder using FastAPI, SQLite, SQLAlchemy or SQLModel, Pydantic, password hashing, JWT auth, RBAC, and local dev CORS, unless the project already has a clearly better backend convention. Do not connect AWS, payment provider, object storage, real file upload, email, OTP provider, OAuth, SSO, or production auth. Do not add backend APIs for GFF AI tools such as Blueprint, ROI, Proposal, Sandbox, Marketplace, Foundry Studio, Talk to Agent, or Assessment. Produce a detailed gap report only. The gap report must cover backend folder needs, database choice, models, seed data, auth endpoints, RBAC roles, client portal CRUD APIs, admin CRUD APIs, frontend API client integration, route guards, migration strategy, local dev scripts, tests, documentation, risks, and exact implementation order. Do not edit files.\"\n./automation/tasks.json:    \"prompt\": \"Create the local MVP backend foundation. Do not touch landing page. Do not modify GFF AI tools. Create a backend folder if it does not exist. Use FastAPI for a local/dev API. Add backend requirements file or pyproject only if consistent with the repository. Include app entrypoint, settings/config module, database module, API router module, health route, CORS config for local Next.js frontend, and a README with local run instructions. Use SQLite local dev database by default. Do not add Docker unless the project already uses it. Do not add AWS, S3, payment, email, OTP provider, OAuth, or production infrastructure. Add .env.example for backend with safe local variables only such as DATABASE_URL, JWT_SECRET, ACCESS_TOKEN_EXPIRE_MINUTES, CORS_ORIGINS. Do not commit real secrets. Add backend .gitignore rules for local database files, __pycache__.env, and virtualenv if needed. Run backend syntax check if possible and frontend lint/build if package scripts exist.\"\n./automation/tasks.json:    \"prompt\": \"Create or update docs/PHASE_5_MVP_BACKEND.md. Do not touch landing page or GFF AI tools. Document how to install backend dependencies, create .env from .env.example, initialize SQLite, run seed, start backend, start frontend, configure NEXT_PUBLIC_API_BASE_URL, login with seeded dev users, and test portal/admin flows. Document that this phase is local/dev MVP only and does not include AWS, storage, payments, email, OTP, OAuth, SSO, production auth hardening, or backend for GFF AI tools. Include troubleshooting for CORS, missing DB, invalid token, and seed rerun. Run lint/build if docs affect build.\"\n./automation/tasks.json:    \"prompt\": \"Create or update docs/PHASE_5_SECURITY_LIMITATIONS.md. Do not touch landing page or GFF AI tools. Document MVP security limitations honestly: JWT in localStorage or dev storage, SQLite local DB, local seed users, no production password reset, no MFA, no refresh token hardening, no httpOnly secure cookie implementation unless already done, no rate limiting, no audit-grade logs, no production RBAC review, no file scanning, no payment compliance. Document required Phase 6 hardening steps: production database, httpOnly secure cookies or hardened session strategy, refresh token rotation, password reset, MFA/SSO optional, rate limiting, audit logs, secrets management, deployment config, CORS hardening. Run lint/build if docs affect build.\"\n./automation/tasks.json:    \"prompt\": \"Add final AWS configuration to the backend. Do not touch landing page. Do not modify GFF AI tools. Update backend env example and settings/config to support AWS_REGION, AWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID, AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY, DYNAMODB_USERS_TABLE, DYNAMODB_CLIENTS_TABLE, DYNAMODB_ITEMS_TABLE, DYNAMODB_ITEMS_TYPE_INDEX, S3_DOCUMENTS_BUCKET, S3_DOCUMENTS_PREFIX, JWT_SECRET, ACCESS_TOKEN_EXPIRE_MINUTES, CORS_ORIGINS, and FRONTEND_BASE_URL. Keep local development support if it already exists. Do not commit real secrets. Do not add unnecessary security features. Run backend import check.\"\n./automation/tasks.json:    \"id\": \"182-phase6-cors-and-deployment-config\",\n./automation/tasks.json:    \"title\": \"Finalize CORS and deployment config\",\n./automation/tasks.json:    \"prompt\": \"Finalize minimal deployment configuration. Do not touch landing page or GFF AI tools. Backend must read CORS_ORIGINS from env and allow the frontend domain. Update docs with backend start command, frontend build command, required env variables, and AWS resource names. Do not add Docker or cloud hosting files unless already required by the current deployment approach. Keep this simple and MVP-ready. Run backend check and frontend build.\"\n./.git/logs/HEAD:82e0c5ea7f29a0afddff5e45df4b246816a93552 5627f3c23443d864b0e00feb8ac51dd43c46751e ayush bansal <forstudyonly101@gmail.com> 1782600154 +0530\tcommit: checkpoint: before-182-phase6-cors-and-deployment-config\n./.git/logs/refs/heads/25-june:82e0c5ea7f29a0afddff5e45df4b246816a93552 5627f3c23443d864b0e00feb8ac51dd43c46751e ayush bansal <forstudyonly101@gmail.com> 1782600154 +0530\tcommit: checkpoint: before-182-phase6-cors-and-deployment-config\n./.git/COMMIT_EDITMSG:checkpoint: before-182-phase6-cors-and-deployment-config\n","success":true}],"durationMs":15682}}
